articles.author: Daphne Psaledakis
articles.description: Russia has received ballistic missiles from Iran and will likely use them in Ukraine within weeks, U.S. Secretary of State Antony Blinken said on Tuesday, warning that cooperation between Moscow and Tehran threatens wider European security.
articles.title: Blinken says Russia received missiles from Iran, warns of threat to European security

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Israeli security forces killed two people in the West Bank city of Tulkarm on Tuesday, Palestinian health authorities said, as the military returned to the city only days after wrapping up one of their biggest operations in months.
articles.title: Two Palestinians killed by Israeli forces in West Bank, Palestinian authorities say

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Russian officials said on Tuesday they shot down at least 15 drones around Moscow overnight in a wave of attacks that set residential buildings on fire, killed a woman and forced more than 30 flights in the capital to be suspended.
articles.title: Ukraine's drones target Moscow, more than 30 airline flights suspended, Russia says

articles.author: Mohammad Salem, Nidal Al-Mughrabi
articles.description: Israeli strikes blasted a huge crater in a designated safe zone in southern Gaza before dawn on Tuesday, setting tents ablaze and burying Palestinian families under sand.
articles.title: Dozens killed, wounded in Israeli strikes on Gaza tent camp

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Typhoon Yagi and the landslides and floods it triggered have killed at least 58 people and 40 others are missing in northern Vietnam, the disaster management agency said on Tuesday.
articles.title: Death toll in Vietnam from Typhoon Yagi rises to 58

articles.author: Max Hunder
articles.description: Ukraine's prosecutor general said on Tuesday that Kyiv suspected a senior Russian air force commander of ordering a missile strike on a children's hospital in central Kyiv in July that killed two people and caused extensive damage.
articles.title: Ukraine identifies Russian suspect in July attack on children's hospital

articles.author: Antony Paone
articles.description: A 71-year-old man on trial in France accused of drugging his wife and inviting dozens of strangers to rape her in their home was hospitalised on Tuesday for medical checks and treatment, his lawyer told journalists.
articles.title: Frenchman on trial for rape of drugged wife is hospitalised, lawyer says

articles.author: Joseph Ax
articles.description: Republican U.S. presidential candidate Donald Trump and Democratic Vice President Kamala Harris will meet in their first and perhaps only debate on Tuesday, a clash that could prove pivotal in their pitched battle for the White House.
articles.title: Trump, Harris to clash at debate that could reshape 2024 race

articles.author: David Ljunggren
articles.description: Justin Trudeau may survive as Canada's prime minister into next year, political analysts say, even though his minority Liberal government is more vulnerable after a small left-wing party withdrew a pledge to support it on key votes.
articles.title: Despite political risks, Trudeau could remain Canada's prime minister into 2025

articles.author: Olena Harmash
articles.description: Ukraine loses more than $11 billion annually in gross domestic product due to landmines laid since Russia's invasion, which create no-go areas and so reduce exports and taxes, according to a report that calls for new approaches to aid and demining.
articles.title: Landmines cost Ukraine $11 bln in GDP each year, says report
